**[Topic 1] Korean Public Transit Network / Graph Dataset**

- **Exploring the Topological Characteristics of Complex Public Transportation Networks: Focus on Variations in Both Single and Integrated Systems in the Seoul Metropolitan Area** (2019, Sustainability / MDPI) — Kim &amp; Jung — Analyzes the integrated subway+bus network of Seoul as a graph, comparing unimodal vs. multimodal topology metrics, directly relevant as a precedent for Korean multimodal graph construction.

- **Statistical Analysis of the Metropolitan Seoul Subway System: Network Structure and Passenger Flows** (2008, Physica A: Statistical Mechanics and Its Applications) — Lee et al. — Examines the topological properties and power-law passenger flow distributions of Seoul Metro, providing a foundational graph-theoretic baseline for Korean subway datasets.

- **Intercity Express Bus Flow in Korea and Its Network Analysis** (2012, Physica A) — Lee &amp; Jung — Constructs and analyzes the intercity express bus network of Korea as a complex graph, directly relevant to the intercity bus component of your nationwide multimodal graph.

- **Does Intercity Transportation Accessibility Matter? Its Effects on Regional Network Centrality in South Korea** (2025, Land / MDPI) — Studies KTX + intercity road network centrality across Korean regions, relevant to the KTX layer of your graph.

- **Network Analysis of World Subway Systems Using Updated Graph Theory** (2009, Transportation Research Record) — Derrible &amp; Kennedy — Analyzes 19 subway systems worldwide (including Seoul) using graph theory, a widely cited methodological reference for transit graph construction and comparison.

---

**[Topic 2] Multimodal Transit Routing Algorithms**

- **ULTRA: Unlimited Transfers for Efficient Multimodal Journey Planning** (2023, Transportation Science) — Baum et al. — Proposes ULTRA, which combines a public transit network with a secondary-mode transfer graph to compute Pareto-optimal journeys, directly applicable to subway+bus+KTX multimodal routing.

- **Transfer Graph Approach for Multimodal Transport Problems** (2008, Springer LNCS / OASIcs) — Müller-Hannemann et al. — Introduces the transfer graph abstraction where multimodal network components are connected via transfer nodes, a foundational model for the graph architecture described in your paper.

- **A Multimodal Transport Network Model and Efficient Algorithms for Building Advanced Traveler Information Systems** (2017, Transportation Research Procedia) — Pyrga et al. — Proposes a multicriteria routing formulation for public transit network itinerary planning, relevant to time-dependent multimodal route search.

- **Routing in Multimodal Transportation Networks with Non-Scheduled Lines** (2022, SEA / LIPIcs) — Potthoff &amp; Witt — Extends Trip-Based routing to non-scheduled modes (e.g., bike-sharing, BRT), relevant to integrating BRT into a time-dependent multimodal graph.

- **An AI-Enhanced Transfer Graph Framework for Time-Dependent Intermodal Transport Optimization** (2025, AI / MDPI) — Integrates ML into transfer-graph models for time-dependent intermodal routing, relevant for future extension of your routing framework.

---

**[Topic 3] Meeting Point / Symmetric Meeting Problem in Transport Networks**

- **Optimal Meeting Points for Public Transit Users** (2018, IEEE ICDE) — Addresses the k-OMPPT problem where a group of users traveling by subway/bus routes find meeting points minimizing aggregate detour distance, the closest direct precedent to your midpoint-finder application in a transit context.

- **Efficient Algorithms for Finding Optimal Meeting Point on Road Networks** (2011, PVLDB / VLDB) — Yan et al. — Proposes efficient algorithms for the optimal meeting-point query where aggregate travel cost from multiple users is minimized on a road network graph, foundational algorithmic reference.

- **Advanced Algorithms for Optimal Meeting Points in Road Networks** (2023, IET Intelligent Transport Systems) — Liu et al. — Proposes randomized adaptive and random-direction heuristics for finding optimal meeting points in large-scale geographic networks, relevant as a scalability comparison.

- **Querying Optimal Routes for Group Meetup** (2021, Data Science and Engineering / Springer) — Formulates the OSR-G problem of finding a meeting POI minimizing maximum users' detour travel distance, relevant to fairness-based midpoint criteria in your application.

- **Calculating Meeting Points for Multi-User Pedestrian Navigation Systems** (2011, Springer LNCS / GIScience) — Discusses Steiner-tree and Euclidean approaches for multi-user meeting-point calculation on street networks, relevant to the geometric vs. network-distance trade-off in midpoint finding.

---

**[Topic 4] Time-Dependent Shortest Path in Transit**

- **Round-Based Public Transit Routing (RAPTOR)** (2015, Transportation Science) — Delling, Pajor &amp; Werneck — Introduces RAPTOR, a non-Dijkstra round-based algorithm optimizing arrival time and transfers in dynamic transit networks, the dominant benchmark algorithm for time-dependent transit routing.

- **Trip-Based Public Transit Routing** (2015, ESA / Springer LNCS) — Witt — Proposes a trip-centric Pareto-optimal routing algorithm with 70 ms 24-hour profile queries on London's network after preprocessing, highly relevant as an efficient time-dependent routing baseline.

- **An Efficient GTFS-Enabled Algorithm for Dynamic Transit Accessibility Analysis** (2017, PLOS ONE) — Proposes a GTFS-based shortest-path algorithm for time-dependent transit travel times, directly relevant for building routing on GTFS schedule data as your paper does.

- **Time-Dependent Shortest-Path Algorithm for Scheduled Service Networks** (1993, Transportation Research Record) — An early foundational reference for time-dependent shortest paths that model transit departure schedules as edge-weight functions of time.

- **Finding the K Shortest Paths in a Schedule-Based Transit Network** (ResearchGate / Transportation Research Part B) — Extends shortest-path methods to schedule-based (time-dependent) transit networks, relevant to the algorithmic layer of your routing system.

---

**[Topic 5] Open Transit Graph Datasets / GTFS**

- **A Collection of Public Transport Network Data Sets for 25 Cities** (2018, Scientific Data / Nature) — Kujala, Weckström, Darst, Mladenović &amp; Saramäki — Publishes curated GTFS-derived graph datasets for 25 cities in multiple network formats, the closest methodological precedent for releasing a standardized transit graph dataset (as your paper does for Korea).

- **Innovative GTFS Data Application for Transit Network Analysis Using a Graph-Oriented Method** (2016, ResearchGate / conference) — Applies graph-oriented methods to GTFS feeds for network analysis, relevant to justifying the GTFS-to-graph pipeline in your paper.

- **Visualizing Public Transit System Operation with GTFS Data: A Case Study of Calgary, Canada** (2020, Heliyon / PMC) — Demonstrates a full workflow of GTFS ingestion, temporal graph construction, and visualization, useful as a methodological comparison for your dataset paper.

- **Route Planning in Transportation Networks** (2016, ACM Computing Surveys) — Bast et al. — Comprehensive survey of routing algorithms on road and transit networks including GTFS-based methods, the standard reference survey for this entire field.

